**One note worth flagging:** AC6 and AC5 together define a half-open boundary `[…, 10000]` — the implementation uses `amount > 10000`, which is correct. The test for AC6 makes this explicit by asserting 10000 succeeds *and* returns the right `refundAmount`, not just that it doesn't throw. That dual assertion is intentional — it's the most common boundary regression pattern (someone changes `>` to `>=` and breaks the boundary silently if you only check for the absence of a throw).

